## Expected behavior and actual behavior.
For Java binding, have added the gdal *** dll folder to the path, and  trying to initialize gdal using  gdalJNI.isAvailable(). but it gives error
 java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: D:\GdalRegister\gdal\gdalalljni.dll: Can't find dependent libraries

## Steps to reproduce the problem.
gdalalljni.dll is unable to find dependent libs.

## Operating system
Window 10

## GDAL version and provenance
Gdal version 204

## Code

```
public class Register {

	protected static final String GDAL_DATA_PATH = "GDAL_DATA";
	protected static final String JAVA_LIBRARY_PATH = "java.library.path";
	protected static final String SEPERATOR = System.getProperty("path.separator");
	protected static final String GDAL_FOLDER = "gdal";
	protected static final String USER_FOLDER = System.getProperty("user.dir");
	protected static final String GDAL_USER_FOLDER = USER_FOLDER + "\\" + GDAL_FOLDER;

	static {
		String newEnv ="";
		String javaEnv = System.getProperty(JAVA_LIBRARY_PATH);
		if (javaEnv.toLowerCase().contains(GDAL_USER_FOLDER)) {
			System.out.println(true);
		} else {
			newEnv =USER_FOLDER + SEPERATOR +  GDAL_USER_FOLDER + SEPERATOR +javaEnv;
			System.out.println(newEnv);
		}
		try {
			setLibraryPath(newEnv);
		} catch (Exception e) {
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
	}
	
	public static void setLibraryPath(String path) throws Exception {
	    System.setProperty("java.library.path", path);
	    //set sys_paths to null so that java.library.path will be reevalueted next time it is needed
	    final Field sysPathsField = ClassLoader.class.getDeclaredField("sys_paths");
	    sysPathsField.setAccessible(true);
	    sysPathsField.set(null, null);
	}

	public static void main(String[] args) {	
		System.out.println(gdalJNI.isAvailable());
       }
}
```

## Output

Native library load failed.
java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: D:\GdalRegister\gdal\gdalalljni.dll: Can't find dependent libraries

